==1-10== {|class="wikitable" align=center |- !Number (digit[s]) !Azerbaijani |- |align=center|'''0 |align=center|'''sıfır |- |align=center|'''1 |align=center|'''bir |- |align=center|'''2 |align=center|'''iki |- |align=center|'''3 |align=center|'''üç |- |align=center|'''4 |align=center|'''dörd |- |align=center|'''5 |align=center|'''beş |- |align=center|'''6 |align=center|'''altı |- |align=center|'''7 |align=center|'''yeddi |- |align=center|'''8 |align=center|'''səkkiz |- |align=center|'''9 |align=center|'''doqquz |- |align=center|'''10 |align=center|'''on |}
==11-19== Once you learn all the numbers from 1 to 10, afterwards it gets much easier. In the case of 11 to 19, just add a number from 1 to 9 after ''on'' to make '''on bir''', '''on iki''', etc. (11 and 12 respectively).
{|class="wikitable" align=center |- !Number (digit[s]) !Azerbaijani |- |align=center|'''11 |align=center|'''on <u>bir</u> |- |align=center|'''12 |align=center|'''on <u>iki</u> |- |align=center|'''13 |align=center|'''on <u>üç</u> |- |align=center|'''14 |align=center|'''on <u>dörd</u> |- |align=center|'''... |align=center|'''... |- |align=center|'''19 |align=center|'''on <u>doqquz</u> |- |align=center|'''20 |align=center|'''iyirmi |}
==20-99== The same thing applies here. Just add the name of a unit after the name of a ten. For example, to make the number 36, just take the words ''otuz'' and ''altı'' to make '''otuz altı''' (36). As long as you know your numbers from 1 to 10, all you really need to learn here are the names of the tens.
{|class="wikitable" align=center |- !Number (digit[s]) !Azerbaijani |- |align=center|'''20 |align=center|'''iyirmi |- |align=center|'''21 |align=center|'''iyirmi <u>bir</u> |- |align=center|'''22 |align=center|'''iyirmi <u>iki</u> |- |align=center|'''... |align=center|'''... |- |align=center|'''30 |align=center|'''otuz |- |align=center|'''40 |align=center|'''qırx |- |align=center|'''50 |align=center|'''əlli |- |align=center|'''60 |align=center|'''altmış |- |align=center|'''70 |align=center|'''yetmiş |- |align=center|'''80 |align=center|'''səksən''' (''həşdad'' also used) |- |align=center|'''90 |align=center|'''doxsan |- |align=center|'''... |align=center|'''... |- |align=center|'''99 |align=center|'''doxsan <u>doqquz</u> |}
==100-999== This also works the same way. Now that you know your tens and units, hundreds are extremely easy. ''Yüz'' is 100. To say 300 in Azerbaijani, all you do is put ''üç'' (3) before ''yüz'', leaving you with '''üç yüz''' (300).
{|class="wikitable" align=center |- !Number (digit[s]) !Azerbaijani |- |align=center|'''100 |align=center|'''yüz |- |align=center|'''101 |align=center|'''yüz <u>bir</u> |- |align=center|'''... |align=center|'''... |- |align=center|'''123 |align=center|'''yüz <u>iyirmi</u> <u>üç</u> |- |align=center|'''... |align=center|'''... |- |align=center|'''200 |align=center|'''<u>iki</u> yüz |- |align=center|'''300 |align=center|'''<u>üç</u> yüz |- |align=center|'''... |align=center|'''... |- |align=center|'''999 |align=center|'''<u>doqquz</u> yüz <u>doxsan</u> <u>doqquz</u> |}
==1000+== Thousands, millions and more work in exactly the same ways. After millions, all values have the same names as their English equivalents, although spelt differently (e.g. trillion = ''trilyon'' in English and Azerbaijani respectively). However, don't feel frightened by this, because the spellings aren't unique (i.e. they all end in ''-yon'').
The only problem you may face among the words below is with the Azerbaijani terms for ''billion''. Although ''bilyon'' can be used, the term ''milyard'' tends to be much more common.
